result.name: AFS
result.description:
Description: Andrew File System (AFS) is jointly developed by Carnegie Mellon University and IBM. It's a common distributed file system which provides users, applications and systems with a suitable shared file system.
Reference: http://www.openafs.org

result.name: AIM
result.description:
Description: AIM (AOL Instant Messenger) is an instant messaging and presence computer program which uses the proprietary OSCAR instant messaging protocol and the TOC protocol to allow registered users to communicate in real time.
Reference: www.aim.com

result.name: BFD
result.description:
Description: Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) is a network protocol used to detect faults between two forwarding engines connected by a link. It provides low-overhead detection of faults even on physical media that don't support failure detection of any kind, such as Ethernet, virtual circuits, tunnels and MPLS Label Switched Paths.
Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bidirectional_Forwarding_Detection

result.name: BGP
result.description:
Description: BGP（Border Gateway Protocol) is a protocol for exchanging routing information between gateway hosts in a network of autonomous systems.
Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Border_Gateway_Protocol

result.name: CHARGEN
result.description: Description: CHARGEN (Character Generator Protocol), defined in RFC864 by Jon Postel, is intended for testing, debugging, and measurement purposes.

result.name: COPA-WEBSERVER
result.description:
Description: COPA-WEBSERVER is mainly used through the Zenon Web server to visualize content that can be invoked and displayed using a web browser. Hillstone industrial equipment supports the protocol detection.
Reference: http://download.copadata.com/fileadmin/user_upload/Downloads/Dokumentation/760SP0/ENGLISH/Manual/zenon_Web_Server.pdf

result.name: DayTime
result.description:
Description: The Daytime Protocol is a service in the Internet Protocol Suite. A host may connect to a server that supports the Daytime Protocol. The server returns a string of the current date and time.
Reference: http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc867

result.name: DHCP-Relay
result.description: Description: DHCP-RELAY agent allows DHCP clients on subnets not directly served by DHCP servers to communicate with DHCP servers.

result.name: DHCPCv6
result.description: Description: DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) defined in RFC1531 is an autoconfiguration protocol that assigns IP addresses to devices on the network automatically.

result.name: DHCPSv6
result.description: Description: DHCP (Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol) defined in RFC1531 is an autoconfiguration protocol that assigns IP addresses to devices on the network automatically.

result.name: DISCARD
result.description: Description: Discard Protocol, defined in RFC863, is an internet protocol intended for testing, debugging, and measurement purposes.

result.name: DNS
result.description: Description: Domain Name System is a core Internet service. It is a hierarchical naming system that translates domain names meaningful to humans into IP addresses that is used for communication between devices at different locations.

result.name: DoT
result.description:
Description: DNS Over HTTPS (DOH) protects DNS data transmission security by using the encrypted HTTPS protocol instead of the traditional UDP protocol during DNS query, effectively avoiding domain name security problems such as domain name hijacking by carriers and DNS cache poisoning.
Reference: https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc8484

result.name: ECHO
result.description: Description: Echo Protocol, defined in RFC862, is an internet protocol for testing and measurement of round-trip times in IP networks.

result.name: FINGER
result.description: Description: The Name/Finger protocol, written by David Zimmerman, is based on RFC 742 (December 1977) as an interface to the name and finger programs that provide status reports on a particular computer system or a particular person at network sites.

result.name: FTP
result.description: Description: FTP (FTP) is used to transfer files between computers on a network.

result.name: FTPS
result.description: Description: FTPS is an extension protocol which adds transport layer security (TLS) and secure socket layer (SSL) encryption protocol support to common file transfer protocol (FTP).

result.name: GIT
result.description:
Description: Git is a distributed open source version control system designed to handle everything from small to very large projects.
Reference: http://git-scm.com

result.name: Gnutella
result.description: Description: Gnutella is a large peer-to-peer network which, at the time of its creation, was the first decentralized peer-to-peer network of its kind, leading to other, later networks adopting the model.

result.name: GOPHER
result.description: Description: The Gopher protocol is an application protocol designed for distributing, searching, and retrieving documents over the Internet.

result.name: GRE

result.name: GTPCv1

result.name: GTPUv1
result.description: Description: GTPu is used for carrying user data within the GPRS Core Network and between the Radio Access Network and the core network.

result.name: GTPv0
result.description: Description: GTP is an IP based protocol used within GSM and UMTS networks.

result.name: HTTP
result.description:
Description: HTTP (Hyper Text Transfer Protocol) is the supporting network protocol for World Wide Web.
Reference: https://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616

result.name: HTTP-EXT
result.description:
Description: HTTP Extension is the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) which is not based on the well known port, the destination port is 7001.
Reference: https://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616

result.name: HTTPS
result.description: Description: HTTPS, the abbreviation for Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure, is a combination of the Hypertext Transfer Protocol with the SSL/TLS protocol to provide encrypted communication and secure identification of a network web server.

result.name: ICMP

result.name: ICMPv6
result.description: Description: The Internet Control Message Protocol Version 6 is a sub-protocol of the TCP/IP protocol suite and is used by the operating system of computers to send error message indication.

Description: Ident Protocol, specified in RFC 1413, is an Internet protocol that helps identify the user of a particularTCP connection. One popular daemon program for providing the ident service is identd.

result.description: Description: IKE(Internet Key Exchange)-NAT is a protocol for IPSec to work through a NAT.

result.name: IMAP4
result.description: Description: Internet message access protocol (commonly known as IMAP) is one of the most prevalent Internet standard protocols for e-mail retrieval. IMAP4 is IMAP version 4.

result.name: IMAPS
result.description:
Description: IMAPS is TLS/SSL-encrypted Internet mail access protocol.
Reference: http://www.ietf.org/rfc/rfc3501.txt

result.name: IP-IP

result.name: IPSEC

result.name: IPv6-IP

result.name: MGCP-CA

result.name: MGCP-UA
result.description: Description: MGCP is an implementation of the Media Gateway Control Protocol architecture for controlling media gateways on Internet Protocol (IP) networks and the public switched telephone network (PSTN). MGCP-UA means User Agent in MGCP architecture.

result.name: MS-SQL

result.name: MySQL

result.name: PING6
